{"title_page": "Stannard Township, Michigan", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Stannard Township, Michigan\n|settlement_type          = [[Civil township]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = BruceCrossingMichiganSignUS45.jpg\n|imagesize                = 275\n|image_caption            = Community of Bruce Crossing along [[U.S. Route 45|US-45]]\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map            =Michigan\n|pushpin_label          =Stannard Township\n|pushpin_label_position =right<!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location within the state of Michigan\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|image_map                = Stannard Township, MI2.png \n|mapsize                  = 250\n|map_caption              = Location within [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon County]]\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Michigan]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = Supervisor\n|leader_name              = William Andrus\n|leader_title1            = [[Municipal clerk|Clerk]]\n|leader_name1             = Karen Mayle\n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           = \n|area_total_sq_mi         = 125.14\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 125.10\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.04\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 790\n|population_density_km2   = \n|population_density_sq_mi = 6.31\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 332\n|elevation_ft             = 1089\n|coordinates              = {{coord|46|33|36|N|89|08|49|W|region:US-MI|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP Code|ZIP code(s)]]\n|postal_code              = 49912 ([[Bruce Crossing, Michigan|Bruce Crossing]])\n|area_code                = [[Area code 906|906]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 26-76180<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1627120<ref>{{gnis|1627120}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|http://www.stannardtwp.com/|Official website}}\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Stannard Township''' is a [[civil township]] of [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]].  The population was 790 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].\n\n==Communities==\n*'''[[Bruce Crossing, Michigan|Bruce Crossing]]''' is an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in the township.\n*'''Paynesville''' is an unincorporated community on M-28 and the Soo Line about three miles east of Bruce Crossing at {{coord|46|31|25|N|89|06|59|W|}}. It was named after the Payne family who owned homesteads nearby. It was a stop on the [[Duluth, South Shore and Atlantic Railway]]. <!--Source: Michigan Place Names, Walter Romig, 1986: Wayne State University Press-->On the SE corner, at the intersection of Blacksmith Rd and N Paynesville Road, in  Paynesville, resides a historic Finnish Lutheran Church.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the township has a total area of {{convert|125.14|sqmi|km2|2}}, of which {{convert|125.10|sqmi|km2|2}} is land and {{convert|0.04|sqmi|km2|2}} (0.02%) is water.\n\nThe western portion of the township is drained by the [[Baltimore River]] and its tributaries. The middle and eastern portions are drained, respectively, by the middle and east branches of the [[Ontonagon River]].\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 833 people, 364 households, and 232 families residing in the township.  The [[population density]] was 6.7 per square mile (2.6/km\u00b2).  There were 518 housing units at an average density of 4.1 per square mile (1.6/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the township was 98.20% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.12% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.84% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], and 0.84% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.60% of the population. 55.6% were of [[finns|Finnish]], 9.5% [[germans|German]] and 7.3% [[United States|American]] ancestry according to [[Census 2000]].\n\nThere were 364 households out of which 23.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 6.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36.0% were non-families. 31.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.23 and the average family size was 2.80.\n\nIn the township the population was spread out with 20.6% under the age of 18, 4.3% from 18 to 24, 25.3% from 25 to 44, 26.8% from 45 to 64, and 22.9% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 45 years. For every 100 females, there were 114.1 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 111.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the township was $24,706, and the median income for a family was $30,938. Males had a median income of $27,708 versus $19,519 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the township was $14,327.  About 8.3% of families and 14.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 20.3% of those under age 18 and 11.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ontonagon County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Townships in Ontonagon County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Townships in Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Stannard Township, Michigan\n|settlement_type          = [[Civil township]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = BruceCrossingMichiganSignUS45.jpg\n|imagesize                = 275\n|image_caption            = Community of Bruce Crossing along [[U.S. Route 45|US-45]]\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map            =Michigan\n|pushpin_label          =Stannard Township\n|pushpin_label_position =right<!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location within the state of Michigan\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|image_map                = Stannard Township, MI2.png \n|mapsize                  = 250\n|map_caption              = Location within [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon County]]\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Michigan]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = Supervisor\n|leader_name              = William Andrus\n|leader_title1            = [[Municipal clerk|Clerk]]\n|leader_name1             = Karen Mayle\n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           = \n|area_total_sq_mi         = 125.14\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 125.10\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.04\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 790\n|population_density_km2   = \n|population_density_sq_mi = 6.31\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 332\n|elevation_ft             = 1089\n|coordinates              = {{coord|46|33|36|N|89|08|49|W|region:US-MI|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP Code|ZIP code(s)]]\n|postal_code              = 49912 ([[Bruce Crossing, Michigan|Bruce Crossing]])\n|area_code                = [[Area code 906|906]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 26-76180<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1627120<ref>{{gnis|1627120}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|http://www.stannardtwp.com/|Official website}}\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Stannard Township''' is a [[civil township]] of [[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon County]], in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]].  The population was 790 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].\n\n==Communities==\n*'''[[Bruce Crossing, Michigan|Bruce Crossing]]''' is an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in the township.\n*'''Paynesville''' is an unincorporated community on M-28 and the Soo Line about three miles east of Bruce Crossing at {{coord|46|31|25|N|89|06|59|W|}}. It was named after the Payne family who owned homesteads nearby. It was a stop on the [[Duluth, South Shore and Atlantic Railway]]. <!--Source: Michigan Place Names, Walter Romig, 1986: Wayne State University Press-->On the SE corner, at the intersection of Blacksmith Rd and N Paynesville Road, in  Paynesville, resides a historic Finnish Lutheran Church.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the township has a total area of {{convert|125.14|sqmi|km2|2}}, of which {{convert|125.10|sqmi|km2|2}} is land and {{convert|0.04|sqmi|km2|2}} (0.02%) is water.\n\nThe western portion of the township is drained by the [[Baltimore River]] and its tributaries. The middle and eastern portions are drained, respectively, by the middle and east branches of the [[Ontonagon River]].\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 833 people, 364 households, and 232 families residing in the township.  The [[population density]] was 6.7 per square mile (2.6/km\u00b2).  There were 518 housing units at an average density of 4.1 per square mile (1.6/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the township was 98.20% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.12% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.84% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], and 0.84% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.60% of the population. 55.6% were of [[finns|Finnish]], 9.5% [[germans|German]] and 7.3% [[United States|American]] ancestry according to [[Census 2000]].\n\nThere were 364 households out of which 23.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 6.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 36.0% were non-families. 31.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.23 and the average family size was 2.80.\n\nIn the township the population was spread out with 20.6% under the age of 18, 4.3% from 18 to 24, 25.3% from 25 to 44, 26.8% from 45 to 64, and 22.9% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 45 years. For every 100 females, there were 114.1 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 111.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the township was $24,706, and the median income for a family was $30,938. Males had a median income of $27,708 versus $19,519 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the township was $14,327.  About 8.3% of families and 14.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 20.3% of those under age 18 and 11.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ontonagon County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Townships in Ontonagon County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Townships in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Notorious4life", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stannard_Township,_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Rimutaka (New Zealand electorate)", "text_new": "{{short description|Current New Zealand electorate}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Rimutaka electorate, 2014.svg|thumb|right|Rimutaka electorate boundaries used since the {{NZ election link|2014}}]]\n'''Rimutaka''' is an [[New Zealand electorates|electorate]] returning one member to the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]]. The current representative is [[Chris Hipkins]], a member of the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]] who has represented the seat since [[2008 New Zealand general election|2008]].<ref>[http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/MPP/MPs/MPs/8/b/9/50MP155641-Hipkins-Chris.htm New Zealand Parliament \u2013 Chris Hipkinsn MP]</ref> A decision to rename the electorate to Remutaka can be expected in April 2020.\n\n==Profile==\nCentred on [[Upper Hutt]] City, the western boundary of the Rimutaka electorate is defined by the [[Hutt River (New Zealand)|Hutt River]] from [[Avalon, New Zealand|Avalon]] and [[Naenae]] in the south, through [[Stokes Valley]], [[Trentham, New Zealand|Trentham]] and Upper Hutt, to [[Te Marua]], [[Kaitoke]], and [[Cloustonville]] in the north. Boundary changes in 2014 saw Rimutaka gain Naenae from the [[Hutt South]] electorate, while losing [[Belmont, Wellington|Belmont]] and [[Kelson]] to Hutt South.<ref name=\"Electorate profile\">{{cite web |title= Rimutaka electorate profile|url= https://www.parliament.nz/resource/en-NZ/DBHOH_Lib_EP_Rimutaka_Electoral_Profile/2876f2efce03171201147a2bdcd66238da607347 |date= June 2015 |publisher= Parliamentary Library |accessdate= 19 December 2016}}{{CC-notice|cc=by3|author=the Parliamentary Library}}</ref>\n\nPopulation growth in the Rimutaka electorate was 2.4% between 2006 and [[2013 New Zealand census|2013]], less than half the national average (5.3%). Of those employed in 2013: 15.0% were clerical and administrative workers (the highest proportion of any general electorate); 12.6% worked in public administration (third-highest); 10.4% were community and personal service workers (fourth-highest). Of those working on census day 2013, 9.1% travelled to work [[Public transport in the Wellington Region#Trains|by train]], the third-highest share among general electorates and almost eight times the New Zealand average (1.2%).<ref name=\"Electorate profile\" />\n\n==History==\nRimutaka was created in {{NZ election link year|1996}} ahead of the change to [[Mixed Member Proportional]] voting. It was created by merging the old Upper Hutt-based seat of {{NZ electorate link|Heretaunga}} with [[Stokes Valley, New Zealand|Stokes Valley]], [[Tait\u0101, New Zealand|Tait\u0101]] and a large section of [[Naenae]] from the defunct {{NZ electorate link|Eastern Hutt}} seat. Eastern Hutt had been held by Labour's [[Paul Swain]] since {{NZ election link year|1987}}, while Heretaunga had been won by National's [[Peter McCardle]] in {{NZ election link year|1990}}. Peter McCardle (who had been re-elected in {{NZ election link year|1993}}) defected to [[New Zealand First]] in 1996. Swain was the clear winner in every election from 1996 to 2005; the inclusion of the working-class areas of [[Hutt City]] helped make Rimutaka safer for the Labour Party, though on the campaign trail in 2008, Labour's chances for winning both party vote and the electorate were summarised as: \"Labour support is 'rock solid' in the south of the electorate but things are volatile in Upper Hutt, where there is 'still work to do'\".<ref name=\"stuff_whatyoutalkingaboutfonz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/vote08/4741314a28627.html |title=Labour stronghold shapes up as a battleground  |date=28 October 2008|accessdate=1 November 2008 |publisher=stuff.co.nz}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2014 boundary review, Rimutaka gained [[Naenae]] and a small part of [[Epuni]] from the {{NZ electorate link|Hutt South}} electorate and lost [[Kelson, New Zealand|Kelson]] and [[Belmont, Wellington|Belmont]] to Hutt South.\n\nFollowing the 2016 Treaty of Waitangi settlement between the Crown and Rangit\u0101ne o Wairarapa and Ng\u0101ti Kahungunu ki Wairarapa T\u0101maki Nui-\u0101-Rua, the electorate's namesake Rimutaka Range was renamed to the Remutaka Range. In the 2019/2020 boundary review, the Representation Commission is proposing to rename the Rimutaka electorate to Remutaka in line with this name change. A final decision is expected in April 2020. The renamed electorate would first be used in the [[2020 New Zealand general election|2020 general election]] and the successful candidate would first represent the area in the [[53rd New Zealand Parliament|53rd Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |title=What's happening now in the boundary review |url= https://vote.nz/boundary-review-2019-2020/whats-happening-now-in-the-boundary-review/ |accessdate=29 January 2020 | publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]]}}</ref>\n\n===Members of Parliament===\nUnless otherwise stated, all MPs terms began and ended at general elections.\n\n'''Key'''\n\n{{Party index link|New Zealand Labour Party}}\n{{Party index link|New Zealand First}}\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! width=100| Election\n! width=175 colspan=2 | Winner \n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1996}}\n| width=5 rowspan=4 bgcolor={{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=4 | [[Paul Swain]]\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|1999}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2002}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2005}}\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|2008}}\n| width=5 rowspan=4 bgcolor={{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=4 | [[Chris Hipkins]]\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2011}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2014}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2017}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===List MPs===\nMembers of Parliament elected from party lists in elections where that person also unsuccessfully contested the Rimutaka electorate. Unless otherwise stated, all MPs terms began and ended at general elections.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! width=100| Election\n! width=175 colspan=2| Winner\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1996}}\n| width=5 bgcolor={{New Zealand First/meta/color}}|\n| [[Peter McCardle]]<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|}\n<sup>1</sup><small> McCardle was the [[New Zealand National Party|National]] MP for {{NZ electorate link|Heretaunga}} from 1990 to 1996</small>\n\n==Election results==\n\n===2017 election===\n{{MMP election box begin |title=[[2017 New Zealand general election|2017 general election]]: Rimutaka<ref name=\"2017 Rimutaka\">{{cite web|title=Official Count Results \u2013 Rimutaka|url=http://electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2017/electorate-details-44.html|publisher=New Zealand Electoral Commission|accessdate=22 December 2017|location=Wellington}}</ref>}}\n{{MMP election box incumbent win|\n |party         = New Zealand Labour Party\n |candidate     = [[Chris Hipkins]]\n |votes         = 21,725\n |percentage    = 55.48\n |change        = +2.97\n |party votes   = 17,180\n |party percent = 43.3\n |party change  = +10.57\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = New Zealand National Party\n |candidate     = Carolyn O'Fallon\n |votes         = 13,116\n |percentage    = 33.49\n |change        = -0.87\n |party votes   = 15,433\n |party percent = 38.9\n |party change  = -2.38\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand\n |candidate     = Stefan Grand-Meyer\n |votes         = 1,815\n |percentage    = 4.63\n |change        = -0.07\n |party votes   = 2,156\n |party percent = 5.43\n |party change  = -4.47\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = New Zealand First\n |candidate     = Talani Meikle\n |votes         = 1,604\n |percentage    = 4.09\n |change        = -0.77\n |party votes   = 2,938\n |party percent = 7.40\n |party change  = -2.83\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = Conservative Party of New Zealand\n |candidate     = Philip Lynch\n |votes         = 356\n |percentage    = 0.91\n |change        