 dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Rimutaka electorate, 2014.svg|thumb|right|Rimutaka electorate boundaries used since the {{NZ election link|2014}}]]\n'''Rimutaka''' is an [[New Zealand electorates|electorate]] returning one member to the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]]. The current representative is [[Chris Hipkins]], a member of the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]] who has represented the seat since [[2008 New Zealand general election|2008]].<ref>[http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/MPP/MPs/MPs/8/b/9/50MP155641-Hipkins-Chris.htm New Zealand Parliament \u2013 Chris Hipkinsn MP]</ref> A decision to rename the electorate to Remutaka can be expected in April 2020.\n\n==Profile==\nCentred on [[Upper Hutt]] City, the western boundary of the Rimutaka electorate is defined by the [[Hutt River (New Zealand)|Hutt River]] from [[Avalon, New Zealand|Avalon]] and [[Naenae]] in the south, through [[Stokes Valley]], [[Trentham, New Zealand|Trentham]] and Upper Hutt, to [[Te Marua]], [[Kaitoke]], and [[Cloustonville]] in the north. Boundary changes in 2014 saw Rimutaka gain Naenae from the [[Hutt South]] electorate, while losing [[Belmont, Wellington|Belmont]] and [[Kelson]] to Hutt South.<ref name=\"Electorate profile\">{{cite web |title= Rimutaka electorate profile|url= https://www.parliament.nz/resource/en-NZ/DBHOH_Lib_EP_Rimutaka_Electoral_Profile/2876f2efce03171201147a2bdcd66238da607347 |date= June 2015 |publisher= Parliamentary Library |accessdate= 19 December 2016}}{{CC-notice|cc=by3|author=the Parliamentary Library}}</ref>\n\nPopulation growth in the Rimutaka electorate was 2.4% between 2006 and [[2013 New Zealand census|2013]], less than half the national average (5.3%). Of those employed in 2013: 15.0% were clerical and administrative workers (the highest proportion of any general electorate); 12.6% worked in public administration (third-highest); 10.4% were community and personal service workers (fourth-highest). Of those working on census day 2013, 9.1% travelled to work [[Public transport in the Wellington Region#Trains|by train]], the third-highest share among general electorates and almost eight times the New Zealand average (1.2%).<ref name=\"Electorate profile\" />\n\n==History==\nRimutaka was created in {{NZ election link year|1996}} ahead of the change to [[Mixed Member Proportional]] voting. It was created by merging the old Upper Hutt-based seat of {{NZ electorate link|Heretaunga}} with [[Stokes Valley, New Zealand|Stokes Valley]], [[Tait\u0101, New Zealand|Tait\u0101]] and a large section of [[Naenae]] from the defunct {{NZ electorate link|Eastern Hutt}} seat. Eastern Hutt had been held by Labour's [[Paul Swain]] since {{NZ election link year|1987}}, while Heretaunga had been won by National's [[Peter McCardle]] in {{NZ election link year|1990}}. Peter McCardle (who had been re-elected in {{NZ election link year|1993}}) defected to [[New Zealand First]] in 1996. Swain was the clear winner in every election from 1996 to 2005; the inclusion of the working-class areas of [[Hutt City]] helped make Rimutaka safer for the Labour Party, though on the campaign trail in 2008, Labour's chances for winning both party vote and the electorate were summarised as: \"Labour support is 'rock solid' in the south of the electorate but things are volatile in Upper Hutt, where there is 'still work to do'\".<ref name=\"stuff_whatyoutalkingaboutfonz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/vote08/4741314a28627.html |title=Labour stronghold shapes up as a battleground  |date=28 October 2008|accessdate=1 November 2008 |publisher=stuff.co.nz}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2014 boundary review, Rimutaka gained [[Naenae]] and a small part of [[Epuni]] from the {{NZ electorate link|Hutt South}} electorate and lost [[Kelson, New Zealand|Kelson]] and [[Belmont, Wellington|Belmont]] to Hutt South.\n\nFollowing the 2016 Treaty of Waitangi settlement between the Crown and Rangit\u0101ne o Wairarapa and Ng\u0101ti Kahungunu ki Wairarapa T\u0101maki Nui-\u0101-Rua, the electorate's namesake Rimutaka Range was renamed to the Remutaka Range. In the 2019/2020 boundary review, the Representation Commission is proposing to rename the Rimutaka electorate to Remutaka in line with this name change. A final decision is expected in April 2020. The renamed electorate would first be used in the [[2020 New Zealand general election|2020 general election]] and the successful candidate would first represent the area in the [[53rd New Zealand Parliament|53rd Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |title=What's happening now in the boundary review |url= https://vote.nz/boundary-review-2019-2020/whats-happening-now-in-the-boundary-review/ |accessdate=29 January 2020 | publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]]}}</ref>\n\n===Members of Parliament===\nUnless otherwise stated, all MPs terms began and ended at general elections.\n\n'''Key'''\n\n{{Party index link|New Zealand Labour Party}}\n{{Party index link|New Zealand First}}\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! width=100| Election\n! width=175 colspan=2 | Winner \n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1996}}\n| width=5 rowspan=4 bgcolor={{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=4 | [[Paul Swain]]\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|1999}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2002}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2005}}\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|2008}}\n| width=5 rowspan=4 bgcolor={{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=4 | [[Chris Hipkins]]\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2011}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2014}}\n|-\n|{{NZ election link|2017}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===List MPs===\nMembers of Parliament elected from party lists in elections where that person also unsuccessfully contested the Rimutaka electorate. Unless otherwise stated, all MPs terms began and ended at general elections.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! width=100| Election\n! width=175 colspan=2| Winner\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1996}}\n| width=5 bgcolor={{New Zealand First/meta/color}}|\n| [[Peter McCardle]]<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|}\n<sup>1</sup><small> McCardle was the [[New Zealand National Party|National]] MP for {{NZ electorate link|Heretaunga}} from 1990 to 1996</small>\n\n==Election results==\n\n===2017 election===\n{{MMP election box begin |title=[[2017 New Zealand general election|2017 general election]]: Rimutaka<ref name=\"2017 Rimutaka\">{{cite web|title=Official Count Results \u2013 Rimutaka|url=http://electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2017/electorate-details-44.html|publisher=New Zealand Electoral Commission|accessdate=22 December 2017|location=Wellington}}</ref>}}\n{{MMP election box incumbent win|\n |party         = New Zealand Labour Party\n |candidate     = [[Chris Hipkins]]\n |votes         = 21,725\n |percentage    = 55.48\n |change        = +2.97\n |party votes   = 17,180\n |party percent = 43.3\n |party change  = +10.57\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = New Zealand National Party\n |candidate     = Carolyn O'Fallon\n |votes         = 13,116\n |percentage    = 33.49\n |change        = -0.87\n |party votes   = 15,433\n |party percent = 38.9\n |party change  = -2.38\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand\n |candidate     = Stefan Grand-Meyer\n |votes         = 1,815\n |percentage    = 4.63\n |change        = -0.07\n |party votes   = 2,156\n |party percent = 5.43\n |party change  = -4.47\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = New Zealand First\n |candidate     = Talani Meikle\n |votes         = 1,604\n |percentage    = 4.09\n |change        = -0.77\n |party votes   = 2,938\n |party percent = 7.40\n |party change  = -2.83\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = Conservative Party of New Zealand\n |candidate     = Philip Lynch\n |votes         = 356\n |percentage    = \n |change        =\n |party votes   = 169\n |party percent = 0.43\n |party change  = -3.58\n}}\n{{MMP election box candidate|\n |party         = ACT New Zealand\n |candidate    