{"title_page": "Tipene O'Regan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Sir Tipene O'Regan\n| image       = Tipene O'Regan (cropped).jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = O'Regan in 2012\n| birth_name  = Stephen Gerard O'Regan\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1939|01|01}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   = Chairman [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] M\u0101ori Trust Board\n| occupation  =\n| relatives   = [[Hana O'Regan]] (daughter)<br>[[Rolland O'Regan]] (father)<br>[[Patrick O'Regan]] (grandfather)\n| nationality = New Zealand\n}}\n'''Sir Tipene O'Regan''' (born '''Stephen Gerard O'Regan''' on 1 January 1939) is a [[New Zealand]] academic and company director.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nThe son of surgeon [[Rolland O'Regan]] and Rena Ruiha (Bradshaw), he is a director of a wide range of South Island M\u0101ori enterprises. He is best known for his role as chairman of the [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] M\u0101ori Trust Board which he guided to successful land and sea fisheries claims before the [[Waitangi Tribunal]], culminating in the Tribunal's reports of 1991 and 1992. He later led claim settlement negotiations leading to the [[Treaty of Waitangi claims and settlements#Ng\u0101i Tahu|1998 settlement]] which made extensive provision for customary rights in fisheries and other natural resources.\n\nIn 1974 he stood alongside his father Rolland on the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]] ticket for the [[Wellington Harbour Board]], however despite polling well he was unsuccessful in winning a seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Catch-upcounting deals double blow |work=[[The Dominion (Wellington)|The Dominion]] |date=15 October 1974}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1994 Birthday Honours|1994 Queen's Birthday Honours]], O'Regan was appointed a [[Knight Bachelor]], for services to the M\u0101ori people and the community.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/53697/supplements/33 ''London Gazette'' (supplement), No. 53697, 10 June 1994]. Retrieved 11 January 2013.</ref>\n\n===Later activities===\n[[File:Tipene O'Regan.jpg|thumb|right|alt = a bronze bust|Bronze bust of O'Regan as part of the [[Twelve Local Heroes]] sculpture]]O'Regan is currently associate lecturer and assistant [[vice chancellor]] ([[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]]) at the [[University of Canterbury]] in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, associated with both the history and M\u0101ori departments. He was awarded an honorary D.Litt. by the University of Canterbury in 1992. In March 2009, O'Regan was commemorated as one of the [[Twelve Local Heroes]] of Christchurch, and a bronze bust of him was unveiled outside the [[Christchurch Arts Centre]].\n\nHe is a director of Milford Dart Ltd, a company which proposed a [[Transport in Milford Sound#Proposed new methods|tunnel]] through the [[Southern Alps (New Zealand)|Southern Alps]] to more than halve the time taken to negotiate the road between resort centres [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]] and [[Milford Sound]]. The proposal had [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] approval but there was opposition because the tunnel would be in a National Park and UNESCO World heritage area.<ref name=\"listener2012\">{{cite web |url= http://www.listener.co.nz/current-affairs/fighting-the-milford-dart-passage/ |title=Fighting the Milford Dart Passage  |work=listener.co.nz |year=2012 |accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> O'Regan argued the \"absurdity of spending over 11 hours in a day to go to Milford from Queenstown\",<ref name=\"listener2012\"/> but in July 2013, the Minister of Conservation, [[Nick Smith (New Zealand politician)|Nick Smith]], declined the proposal because of significant environmental impacts.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1307/S00289/minister-declines-milford-dart-tunnel-proposal.htm|title=Minister declines Milford Dart Tunnel proposal|work=scoop.co.nz |year=2012 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nO'Regan was a member of the [[New Zealand Geographic Board]] from 1985 to 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kahurumanu.co.nz/our-people/ta-tipene-o-regan/sir-tipene-oregan-full-biography |title=T\u0101 Tipene O'Regan |website=K\u0101 Huru Manu |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> and from 2010 he has co-chaired the Constitutional Advisory Panel, which is seeking public input on constitutional reform in [[New Zealand]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.atns.net.au/agreement.asp?EntityID=1728 atns.net.au]\n* [http://www.nzine.co.nz/views/tipene.html nzine.co.nz]\n* [http://www.maori.canterbury.ac.nz/people/oregan.shtml maori.canterbury.ac.nz]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050920105430/http://www.hist.canterbury.ac.nz/people/oregan.shtml hist.canterbury.ac.nz]\n\n{{Twelve Local Heroes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oregan, Tipene}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand academics]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Ng\u0101i Tahu]]\n[[Category:Treaty of Waitangi]]\n[[Category:University of Canterbury faculty]]\n[[Category:New Zealand M\u0101ori academics]]\n[[Category:University of Canterbury alumni]]\n[[Category:New Zealand businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People educated at St. Patrick's College, Wellington]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Labour Party politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Sir Tipene O'Regan\n| image       = Tipene O'Regan (cropped).jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = O'Regan in 2012\n| birth_name  = Stephen Gerard O'Regan\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1939|01|01}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   = Chairman [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] M\u0101ori Trust Board\n| occupation  =\n| relatives   = [[Hana O'Regan]] (daughter)<br>[[Rolland O'Regan]] (father)<br>[[Patrick O'Regan]] (grandfather)\n| nationality = New Zealand\n}}\n'''Sir Tipene O'Regan''' (born '''Stephen Gerard O'Regan''' on 1 January 1939) is a [[New Zealand]] academic and company director.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nThe son of surgeon [[Rolland O'Regan]] and Rena Ruiha (Bradshaw), he is a director of a wide range of South Island M\u0101ori enterprises. He is best known for his role as chairman of the [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] M\u0101ori Trust Board which he guided to successful land and sea fisheries claims before the [[Waitangi Tribunal]], culminating in the Tribunal\u2019s reports of 1991 and 1992. He later led claim settlement negotiations leading to the [[Treaty of Waitangi claims and settlements#Ng\u0101i Tahu|1998 settlement]] which made extensive provision for customary rights in fisheries and other natural resources.\n\nIn 1974 he stood alongside his father Rolland on the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]] ticket for the [[Wellington Harbour Board]], however despite polling well he was unsuccessful in winning a seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Catch-upcounting deals double blow |work=[[The Dominion (Wellington)|The Dominion]] |date=15 October 1974}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1994 Birthday Honours|1994 Queen's Birthday Honours]], O'Regan was appointed a [[Knight Bachelor]], for services to the M\u0101ori people and the community.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/53697/supplements/33 ''London Gazette'' (supplement), No. 53697, 10 June 1994]. Retrieved 11 January 2013.</ref>\n\n===Later activities===\n[[File:Tipene O'Regan.jpg|thumb|right|alt = a bronze bust|Bronze bust of O'Regan as part of the [[Twelve Local Heroes]] sculpture]]O'Regan is currently associate lecturer and assistant [[vice chancellor]] ([[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]]) at the [[University of Canterbury]] in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, associated with both the history and M\u0101ori departments. He was awarded an honorary D.Litt. by the University of Canterbury in 1992. In March 2009, O'Regan was commemorated as one of the [[Twelve Local Heroes]] of Christchurch, and a bronze bust of him was unveiled outside the [[Christchurch Arts Centre]].\n\nHe is a director of Milford Dart Ltd, a company which proposed a [[Transport in Milford Sound#Proposed new methods|tunnel]] through the [[Southern Alps (New Zealand)|Southern Alps]] to more than halve the time taken to negotiate the road between resort centres [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]] and [[Milford Sound]]. The proposal had [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] approval but there was opposition because the tunnel would be in a National Park and UNESCO World heritage area.<ref name=\"listener2012\">{{cite web |url= http://www.listener.co.nz/current-affairs/fighting-the-milford-dart-passage/ |title=Fighting the Milford Dart Passage  |work=listener.co.nz |year=2012 |accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> O'Regan argued the \"absurdity of spending over 11 hours in a day to go to Milford from Queenstown\",<ref name=\"listener2012\"/> but in July 2013, the Minister of Conservation, [[Nick Smith (New Zealand politician)|Nick Smith]], declined the proposal because of significant environmental impacts.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA1307/S00289/minister-declines-milford-dart-tunnel-proposal.htm|title=Minister declines Milford Dart Tunnel proposal|work=scoop.co.nz |year=2012 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nO'Regan was a member of the [[New Zealand Geographic Board]] from 1985 to 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kahurumanu.co.nz/our-people/ta-tipene-o-regan/sir-tipene-oregan-full-biography |title=T\u0101 Tipene O'Regan |website=K\u0101 Huru Manu |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref> and from 2010 he has co-chaired the Constitutional Advisory Panel, which is seeking public input on constitutional reform in [[New Zealand]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.atns.net.au/agreement.asp?EntityID=1728 atns.net.au]\n* [http://www.nzine.co.nz/views/tipene.html nzine.co.nz]\n* [http://www.maori.canterbury.ac.nz/people/oregan.shtml maori.canterbury.ac.nz]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050920105430/http://www.hist.canterbury.ac.nz/people/oregan.shtml hist.canterbury.ac.nz]\n\n{{Twelve Local Heroes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oregan, Tipene}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand academics]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Ng\u0101i Tahu]]\n[[Category:Treaty of Waitangi]]\n[[Category:University of Canterbury faculty]]\n[[Category:New Zealand M\u0101ori academics]]\n[[Category:University of Canterbury alumni]]\n[[Category:New Zealand businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People educated at St. Patrick's College, Wellington]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Labour Party politicians]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and career:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tipene_O%27Regan"}
{"title_page": "Jason Davis (baseball)", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|image=Jason Davis (cropped).jpg\n|caption=Davis with the [[Indianapolis Indians]] in 2009\n|name=Jason Davis\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1980|5|8}}\n|birth_place=[[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=September 9\n|debutyear=2002\n|debutteam=Cleveland Indians\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=September 20\n|finalyear=2008\n|finalteam=Pittsburgh Pirates\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win (baseball)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=22\u201326\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=4.82\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=269\n|teams=\n*[[Cleveland Indians]] ({{By|2002}}\u2013{{By|2007}})\n*[[Seattle Mariners]] ({{By|2007}})\n*[[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{By|2008}})\n}}\n'''Jason Thomas Davis''' (born May 8, 1980) is a former [[Major League Baseball]] [[right-handed]] [[pitcher]]. He played in MLB for the [[Cleveland Indians]], [[Seattle Mariners]] and [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Cleveland Indians===\nDavis attended [[Cleveland State Community College]], was drafted by the [[Cleveland Indians]] in the 21st round of the [[1999 Major League Baseball Draft]], and signed May 18, {{By|2000}}. He spent his first season as a professional in with the Rookie-level [[Burlington Royals|Burlington Athletics]], making 10 starts going 4-4 with a 4.40 ERA.\n\nDavis elevated himself to prospect status in {{By|2001}}, going 14-6 with a 2.70 ERA in 27 starts at Class-A [[Columbus RedStixx]] of the [[South Atlantic League]]. He led the club in wins, which finished tied for third in the league. His 2.70 ERA was also the seventh lowest mark in the league as he also finished tied for fourth with 27 starts.\n\nIn {{By|2002}} Davis had a breakout season, beginning the year with the Class-A [[Kinston Indians]] of the [[Carolina League]] before compiling an impressive ERA of 1.84 in three outings with Cleveland to end the season. Davis began the season at Kinston, losing five of his first six decisions through June 3. He tossed a four-hit, complete game nine inning shutout on June 8. Over his last five starts at Kinston he was 2-1 with a 3.15 ERA and was promoted to the Double-A [[Akron Aeros]] for the second half of the season on July 10. He got off to a shaky start in with Akron, going 1-2 with a 5.40 ERA in four starts. Over his last five Akron starts, Davis was 5-0 with a 1.17 ERA. He was promoted to the big leagues on September 9 when his contract was purchased from Akron after the Aeros were eliminated from the playoffs. He made his Major League debut that night in relief of [[Jaret Wright]] against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] tossing four innings, and giving up one run, yielding a solo home run to [[Eric Hinske]]. Davis made his first major league start on September 14 against the [[Minnesota Twins]] and did not get a decision in the 3-2 Twins win. He picked up his first major league win on September 20 against the [[Kansas City Royals]] in a 6-2 win.\n\nDavis was one of the Indians' most consistent and durable starting pitchers, spending his first full season in the big leagues in {{mlby|2003}}. He led all [[American League]] rookie pitchers with 165-and-one-third innings pitched. Davis also finished sixth among AL rookie pitchers in strikeouts with 85, third in starts with 27, second in ERA with a 4.68 clip and tied for fourth in wins with eight. He pitched the first complete game of his Major League career in start against the [[Detroit Tigers]] on June 18.\n\nHe spent the first half of the {{mlby|2004}} season in the a starting role before a trip to Buffalo and successful transition to the bullpen turned around his season. He was converted to relief after his final start of September 4 against the [[Anaheim Angels]].\n\nDavis enjoyed four stints with the big league club in {{mlby|2005}} and spent the remainder of his time in the Triple-A [[Buffalo Bisons]]' rotation.\n\nIn {{mlby|2006}} Davis spent the entire season in relief for the first time in his career. He allowed only 1 [[home run]] in 55{{frac|1|3}} [[innings pitched]]. He was optioned to Triple-A Buffalo out of spring training but was recalled two days later after [[CC Sabathia]] was injured on opening night. Davis went 2-1 with a  5.04 [[Earned run average|ERA]] in 21 outings before being optioned to Buffalo on June 13. Davis spent 5 weeks in Buffalo where he was 0-2 with 4 [[save (baseball)|saves]] and a 0.54 ERA in 11 relief appearances, limiting Triple-A hitters to a .138 [[batting average (baseball)|average]] against him. He was recalled on July 21 after [[Bob Wickman]] was traded. Over his second stint with Cleveland he was 1-1 with a 2.16 ERA in 18 outings and on the year 24 of his 39 outings were scoreless. Davis earned his first career save on August 3 against the [[Boston Red Sox]].\n\nDavis began the {{mlby|2007}} season with Cleveland, making eight relief appearances with no record and a 4.76 ERA.\n\n===Seattle Mariners===\nHe was traded to the [[Seattle Mariners]] from Cleveland on May 13, {{By|2007}}, for a player to be named later. Davis made 16 [[Relief pitcher|relief]] appearances going 2-0 with a 6.31 ERA in 25{{frac|2|3}} innings. He was later reassigned to the Triple-A [[Tacoma Rainiers]], made five starts from July 24 to August 16, going 0-2 with a 7.11 ERA in 25{{frac|1|3}} innings. He allowed a .346 average in Triple-A, including a .458 average to leadoff hitters.\n\n===Pittsburgh Pirates===\n[[File:Jason Davis Winds Up (3737322916).jpg|thumb|right|Jason Davis pitching for the Indians]]After the {{mlby|2007}} season, Davis elected for [[Free agent|free agency]] and signed a minor league contract with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]]. He was released on March 27, {{By|2008}}. On March 30, Davis signed a minor league contract with the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] and he began the season in the rotation at Triple-A [[Indianapolis Indians]], going 6-9 with a 4.41 ERA in 21 games, 20 starts. Davis went a season-high eight innings to win his final Triple-A start against the [[Charlotte Knights]] on July 22, allowing two runs on seven hits. He was called up to Pittsburgh where he made appearances, going 2-4 with a 5.29 ERA in 34 innings. Davis made his first start against the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] on August 10, holding the Phillies to no earned runs on four hits and four walks over six innings. He declined a minor league assignment on December 10, 2008, becoming a free agent. He had been mentioned as possibly going to pitch in [[Japan]],<ref>[http://www.fantasysp.com/player/mlb/Jason_Davis/163238]</ref> but instead re-signed with the Pirates.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn Davis's spare time, he pursues an interest in [[taxidermy]]. His home was filled with trophies that he hunted and then stuffed and mounted himself, including the heads of 21 deer. He was married to a beautiful woman with 4 amazing kids, Lily, Jaxon, Landon, and Sadie. But Davis decided that what he had wasn't enough to fulfill his lifestyle so he decided to leave his family for one of his coworkers. She was also married. She has no eyebrows nor personality. <ref name=pitcher_hunts>Finder, Chuck. \"[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/09055/951170-63.stm Pitcher hunts for spot in rotation]\", The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, February 24, 2009.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=425186|espn=5346|br=d/davisja02|fangraphs=1598|brm=davis-003jas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jason}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Akron Aeros players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland State Cougars baseball players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Columbus RedStixx players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Indians players]]\n[[Category:Kinston Indians players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Rainiers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|image=Jason Davis (cropped).jpg\n|caption=Davis with the [[Indianapolis Indians]] in 2009\n|name=Jason Davis\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1980|5|8}}\n|birth_place=[[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=September 9\n|debutyear=2002\n|debutteam=Cleveland Indians\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=September 20\n|finalyear=2008\n|finalteam=Pittsburgh Pirates\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win (baseball)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=22\u201326\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=4.82\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=269\n|teams=\n*[[Cleveland Indians]] ({{By|2002}}\u2013{{By|2007}})\n*[[Seattle Mariners]] ({{By|2007}})\n*[[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{By|2008}})\n}}\n'''Jason Thomas Davis''' (born May 8, 1980) is a former [[Major League Baseball]] [[right-handed]] [[pitcher]]. He played in MLB for the [[Cleveland Indians]], [[Seattle Mariners]] and [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Cleveland Indians===\nDavis attended [[Cleveland State Community College]], was drafted by the [[Cleveland Indians]] in the 21st round of the [[1999 Major League Baseball Draft]], and signed May 18, {{By|2000}}. He spent his first season as a professional in with the Rookie-level [[Burlington Royals|Burlington Athletics]], making 10 starts going 4-4 with a 4.40 ERA.\n\nDavis elevated himself to prospect status in {{By|2001}}, going 14-6 with a 2.70 ERA in 27 starts at Class-A [[Columbus RedStixx]] of the [[South Atlantic League]]. He led the club in wins, which finished tied for third in the league. His 2.70 ERA was also the seventh lowest mark in the league as he also finished tied for fourth with 27 starts.\n\nIn {{By|2002}} Davis had a breakout season, beginning the year with the Class-A [[Kinston Indians]] of the [[Carolina League]] before compiling an impressive ERA of 1.84 in three outings with Cleveland to end the season. Davis began the season at Kinston, losing five of his first six decisions through June 3. He tossed a four-hit, complete game nine inning shutout on June 8. Over his last five starts at Kinston he was 2-1 with a 3.15 ERA and was promoted to the Double-A [[Akron Aeros]] for the second half of the season on July 10. He got off to a shaky start in with Akron, going 1-2 with a 5.40 ERA in four starts. Over his last five Akron starts, Davis was 5-0 with a 1.17 ERA. He was promoted to the big leagues on September 9 when his contract was purchased from Akron after the Aeros were eliminated from the playoffs. He made his Major League debut that night in relief of [[Jaret Wright]] against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] tossing four innings, and giving up one run, yielding a solo home run to [[Eric Hinske]]. Davis made his first major league start on September 14 against the [[Minnesota Twins]] and did not get a decision in the 3-2 Twins win. He picked up his first major league win on September 20 against the [[Kansas City Royals]] in a 6-2 win.\n\nDavis was one of the Indians' most consistent and durable starting pitchers, spending his first full season in the big leagues in {{mlby|2003}}. He led all [[American League]] rookie pitchers with 165-and-one-third innings pitched. Davis also finished sixth among AL rookie pitchers in strikeouts with 85, third in starts with 27, second in ERA with a 4.68 clip and tied for fourth in wins with eight. He pitched the first complete game of his Major League career in start against the [[Detroit Tigers]] on June 18.\n\nHe spent the first half of the {{mlby|2004}} season in the a starting role before a trip to Buffalo and successful transition to the bullpen turned around his season. He was converted to relief after his final start of September 4 against the [[Anaheim Angels]].\n\nDavis enjoyed four stints with the big league club in {{mlby|2005}} and spent the remainder of his time in the Triple-A [[Buffalo Bisons]]' rotation.\n\nIn {{mlby|2006}} Davis spent the entire season in relief for the first time in his career. He allowed only 1 [[home run]] in 55{{frac|1|3}} [[innings pitched]]. He was optioned to Triple-A Buffalo out of spring training but was recalled two days later after [[CC Sabathia]] was injured on opening night. Davis went 2-1 with a  5.04 [[Earned run average|ERA]] in 21 outings before being optioned to Buffalo on June 13. Davis spent 5 weeks in Buffalo where he was 0-2 with 4 [[save (baseball)|saves]] and a 0.54 ERA in 11 relief appearances, limiting Triple-A hitters to a .138 [[batting average (baseball)|average]] against him. He was recalled on July 21 after [[Bob Wickman]] was traded. Over his second stint with Cleveland he was 1-1 with a 2.16 ERA in 18 outings and on the year 24 of his 39 outings were scoreless. Davis earned his first career save on August 3 against the [[Boston Red Sox]].\n\nDavis began the {{mlby|2007}} season with Cleveland, making eight relief appearances with no record and a 4.76 ERA.\n\n===Seattle Mariners===\nHe was traded to the [[Seattle Mariners]] from Cleveland on May 13, {{By|2007}}, for a player to be named later. Davis made 16 [[Relief pitcher|relief]] appearances going 2-0 with a 6.31 ERA in 25{{frac|2|3}} innings. He was later reassigned to the Triple-A [[Tacoma Rainiers]], made five starts from July 24 to August 16, going 0-2 with a 7.11 ERA in 25{{frac|1|3}} innings. He allowed a .346 average in Triple-A, including a .458 average to leadoff hitters.\n\n===Pittsburgh Pirates===\n[[File:Jason Davis Winds Up (3737322916).jpg|thumb|right|Jason Davis pitching for the Indians]]After the {{mlby|2007}} season, Davis elected for [[Free agent|free agency]] and signed a minor league contract with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]]. He was released on March 27, {{By|2008}}. On March 30, Davis signed a minor league contract with the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] and he began the season in the rotation at Triple-A [[Indianapolis Indians]], going 6-9 with a 4.41 ERA in 21 games, 20 starts. Davis went a season-high eight innings to win his final Triple-A start against the [[Charlotte Knights]] on July 22, allowing two runs on seven hits. He was called up to Pittsburgh where he made appearances, going 2-4 with a 5.29 ERA in 34 innings. Davis made his first start against the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] on August 10, holding the Phillies to no earned runs on four hits and four walks over six innings. He declined a minor league assignment on December 10, 2008, becoming a free agent. He had been mentioned as possibly going to pitch in [[Japan]],<ref>[http://www.fantasysp.com/player/mlb/Jason_Davis/163238]</ref> but instead re-signed with the Pirates.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn Davis's spare time, he pursues an interest in [[taxidermy]]. His home was filled with trophies that he hunted and then stuffed and mounted himself, including the heads of 21 deer. He was married to a beautiful woman with 4 amazing kids, Lily, Jaxon, Landon, and Sadie. But Davis decided that what he had wasn't enough to fulfill his lifestyle so he decided to leave his family for one of his coworkers. She was also married. She has no eyebrows nor personality. <ref></ref><ref name=pitcher_hunts>Finder, Chuck. \"[http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/09055/951170-63.stm Pitcher hunts for spot in rotation]\", The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, February 24, 2009.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=425186|espn=5346|br=d/davisja02|fangraphs=1598|brm=davis-003jas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jason}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Akron Aeros players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland State Cougars baseball players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Columbus RedStixx players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Indians players]]\n[[Category:Kinston Indians players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Rainiers players]]\n", "name_user": "Speedlimit20", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jason_Davis_(baseball)"}
{"title_page": "Jacky winter", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jacky winter \n| image = Jacky Winter - Glen Davis.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704769/0 |title=''Microeca fascinans'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Microeca\n| species = fascinans\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''jacky winter''' (''Microeca fascinans'') is a small grey-brown robin found commonly throughout [[Australia]] and also in [[Papua New Guinea]]. The jacky winter acquired its name due to rapid and strong vocalisations, which sound like ''jacky-jacky winter-winter''.<ref name=Simpson>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia ISBN 067087918-5.</ref> Their call is also often referred to as sounding like ''peter-peter-peter''.<ref name=Slater>Slater, Peter (1974) A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines. Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref> Its habitats include open woodlands and farmlands.\n\n== Taxonomy and distribution ==\n\nThe jacky winter belongs to the family of [[Australasia]]n robins and flycatchers ''[[Petroicidae]]''. This family includes around 49 species in around 19 genera that are all endemic to [[Australasia]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref><ref>Loynes, K., Joseph, L. and Keogh, J. S. 2009. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790309002000 Multi-locus phylogeny clarifies the systematics of the Australo-Papuan robins (Family Petroicidae, Passeriformes)]. \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 53: 212-219. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2009.05.012}}</ref> The family ''[[Petroicidae]]'' evolved in a similar way to the [[Australo-Papuan]] warblers (''[[Acanthizidae]]'')\u2014the latter evolved in isolation from similar families to them, namely ''[[Parulidae]]'' and ''[[Sylviidae]]'', which occupied comparable niches in other continental regions, such as [[Central America|Central]][[South America|/South America]] and [[Eurasia]], respectively.<ref>Ericson, p. G. P., Irestedt, M. and Johansson, U.S. 2003. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03121.x/abstract?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&userIsAuthenticated=false Evolution, biogeography, and patters of diversification in passerine birds]. \u2013 J. Avian. Biol. 34: 3-15. {{DOI|10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03121.x}}</ref> ''[[Petroicidae]]'' evolved in the [[Australo-Papuan]] area to fill an ecological niche, which was already being used by New World flycatchers (''[[Tyrannidae]]'') in [[North America]] and [[South America]], and by Old World flycatchers (''[[Muscicapidae]]'') in [[Europe]], [[Africa]], and [[Asia]]. This is an example of [[convergent evolution]].<ref name=\"Chris\">Christidis, L., Irestedt, M., Rowe, D., Boles, W. E. and Norman, J. A. 2011. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790311003587 Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA phylogenies reveal a complex evolutionary history in the Australasian robin (Passeriformes: Petroicidae).] \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 61: 726-738. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2011.08.014}}</ref><ref>Sangster, G., Alstrom, P., Forsmark, E. and Olsson, U. 2010. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790310003076 Multi-locus phylogenetic analysis of Old World chats and flycatchers reveals extensive paraphyly at family, subfamily and genus level (Aves Muscicapidae)] \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 57: 380-392. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2010.07.008}}</ref>\n\nThe generic name ''Microeca'' derives from the Greek ''micros'' meaning 'small' and ''oikos'' meaning 'house'. This refers to the fact that they build the smallest nest of any Australian bird.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref> The specific name ''fascinans'' is Latin for 'fascinating' and derives from ''fascinare'' meaning 'to bewitch'.<ref name=Helm></ref>\n\nOther vernacular names for the jacky winter are brown flycatcher, peter peter, postboy, spinks and stumpbird.<ref name=Slater></ref><ref>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref>\n\nThere are three races of jacky winter found in [[Australia]]. ''Microeca fascinans fascinans'' (''leucophaea'') is the most familiar race, and is found in central and eastern [[Queensland]], [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], and southeastern [[South Australia]]. There are also ''Microeca fascinans assimilis'', which is found in [[South Australia]] and south [[Western Australia]], and ''Microeca fascinans pallida'', which is found in northern and western [[Queensland]], [[Northern Territory]], and the [[Kimberley]] in Western Australia.<ref name=Simpson></ref><ref name=\"Chris\" /><ref>Morcombe, Michael (2012) Field guide to Australian birds. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref><ref name=\"reid\">Reid, J. R. W. and Gillen, J. S. 2013. [http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/files/d137ff65-3033-48e5-8200-a2de00e18b97/cooper-catchment-2013-birds-rep.pdf. Riparian bird assembladges of Cooper Creek, South Australia]. \u2013 South Australian Arid Lands Natural Resources Management Board.</ref> ''Microeca fascinans zimmeri'' is a subspecies of jacky winter found in Papua New Guinea <ref>Bell, H. L. 2008. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1474-919X.1982.tb03772.x/abstract Abundance and seasonality of the savannah avifauna at Port Moresby, Papua New Guinea]. \u2013 Ibis 124: 252-274. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1474-919X.1982.tb03772.x}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nThe jacky winter is around 12 \u2013 14&nbsp;cm in length (including the tail) and its weight varies from 14 \u2013 18 g.<ref name=\"wood\">Wood, K. A, Thompson, N. and Ley, A. J. 2008. [http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=407981259692578;res=IELHSS Breeding Territories and Breeding Success of the Jacky Winter Microeca fasinans in South-eastern Queensland]. \u2013 Australian Field Ornithology 25: 121-131. {{ISSN|1448-0107}}</ref> The plumage of ''M. f. fascinans'' includes a greyish breast with white on the bottom half, its head and back is greyish-brown, while its wings are a darker brown with white edges. The bill is black, it has a narrow eye-line and a buff [[alula]] stripe. The tail of ''M. f. fascinans'' is blackish brown with white outer feathers. Its legs are black. Subspecies ''M. f. assimilis'' is very similar to ''M. f. fascinans''; however, it is darker, with more grey over the breast and flanks, covering up the white which is seen on ''M. f. fascinans''.<ref name=\"wood\" /> ''M. f. pallida'' is smaller than the other two subspecies, being only around 13&nbsp;cm. ''M. f. pallida'' is much more pallid than the other subspecies, and is usually a sandy brown colour.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Behaviour ==\n[[File:Jacky-winter96.ogg|thumb|300px|Rush Creek, south-east Queensland]]\n\nThe jacky winter can be heard vocalising before sunrise and usually stops towards the middle of the day. Occasionally closer to sunset, it can be heard again.<ref name=\"Kea\">Keast, A. 1994. [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?paper=MU9940230 The Annual Cycle in a Vocalisation Context: a Comparison of the Eastern Yellow Robin Eopsaltria australis and the Jacky Winter Microeca leucophaea.] \u2013 Emu 94: 230-238. {{doi|10.1071/MU9940230}}</ref> During the day they can be seen perched atop trees and posts, [[preening]] their [[feathers]] or even sunning to kill the [[parasites]], which may be present in amongst the feathers.<ref>Moyer, B. R. and Wagenbach, G. E. 1995. [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4089047?sid=21106224627453&uid=3737536&uid=4&uid=2 Sunning by Black Noddies (''Anous minutus'') may kill chewing lice (''Quadraceps hopkinsi'')]. \u2013 Auk. 112: 1073-1077. {{ISSN|0004-8038}}</ref>\n\n=== Diet ===\n\nThe jacky winter is an [[insectivore]] and a sit-and-search [[predator]], which moves amongst perches to locate food. This is a continuous activity that can cover long distances in order to find prey items.<ref name=\"rec\" /> The jacky winter has two methods of hunting, which include hawking and ground-pouncing. Hawking is when a bird flies and drops to the ground, grabbing their prey during flight, while ground-pouncing is when they fly from a perch, grabbing prey as they land.<ref name=\"mill\">Miller, J. R. and Cale, P. 2000. [http://www.esajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1890/1051-0761(2000)010%5B1732:BMAHUB%5D2.0.CO%3B2 Behavioural mechanisms and habitat use by birds in a fragmented agricultural landscape]. \u2013 Ecological Application. 10: 1732-1748. {{DOI|10.1890/1051-0761(2000)010}}</ref> Both of these hunting styles are used quite commonly by the jacky winter.<ref name=\"rec\" /><ref name=\"mill\" /><ref name=\"re\">Recher, H. F. and Davis Jr, W. E. 2002. [http://www.rswa.org.au/publications/Journal/85%282%29/recher85%282%29.pdf Foraging profile of a Salmon Gum woodland avifauna in Western Australia.] - Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia. 85: 103-111.</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Jacky winter nesting.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Female nesting]]\nIn many species of birds, the male plumage is quite bright and flamboyant to attract the opposite sex in hope of finding a partner to mate with. The jacky winter is instead a [[sexually monomorphic]] bird, which means that both the male and female are almost identical in appearance.<ref name=\"wood\" /> Rather than plumage playing a significant role in attracting the opposite sex, the jacky winter male uses song to attract a female during courtship.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> In the eastern states of Australia, the jacky winter breeds mostly to the west of the Great Dividing Range, where a suitable habitat of eucalyptus woodland is present. They build a small, open cup-shaped [[nest]], which is often made from grass and bark strips held together by spider webs. The nest is built in an exposed position, usually on a fork of a branch.<ref name=\"wood\" />\n\nThe breeding season of jacky winters occurs from September to November. Leading up to September, singing from the males is at its highest peak, then as the [[nestlings]] are born around late September, the singing becomes quite minimal.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> In late October, the singing increases again, lasting until early November, when the females lay a second [[brooding|brood]] of the season. By late November with the hatching of the young, the males stop singing, making vocalisations almost non-existent from then on. It stays like this until the birds have left the area.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> The nesting period lasts for 15 to 20 days, while the [[Egg incubation|incubation]] is between 16 and 18 days. Only the female will [[Egg incubation|incubate]] the eggs, while the male will help feed the young once they have hatched. 92 per cent of the time, the female will lay only two eggs per clutch.<ref name=\"wood\" />  It is uncommon for this number to vary, since many different [[environment (biophysical)|environmental]] factors determine the number of eggs per clutch in order to maximize the survival rate of fledglings from the nest.<ref>Winkler, D. W. and Walter, J. R. 1983. [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-4615-6781-3_2 The determination of clutch size in precocial birds]. \u2013 Current Ornithology. 1: 33-68. {{DOI|10.1007/978-1-4615-6781-3_2}}</ref>\n\nTerritory size of the jacky winter has been recorded at 1.7 ha, which is similar to other species of ''[[Petroicidae]]'', such as the [[flame robin]] and [[scarlet robin]]. The jacky winter seems to favour habitats for breeding that contain a [[eucalyptus]] box woodland or open box woodland, which have patches of box trees and isolated live trees. Fallen logs and stumps are also favoured in habitat selection.<ref name=\"wood\" /> The jacky winter holds these territories by perching on top of these eucalyptus trees and keeping a regular sustained call. The breeding density of jacky winters is about 17.2&nbsp;ha for one pair.<ref name=\"wood\" /> The jacky winter is known to defend their territory all year around.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Status ==\n\nThe jacky winter is a common species of bird found throughout [[Australia]], and is described as a bird of [[least concern]] by the [[IUCN]] (International Union for Conservation of Nature). Like many other small woodland birds in [[Australia]], the jacky winter populations are declining and are considered to be a common species but decreasing.<ref name=\"rei\">Reid, J. R. W. 1999. [http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/resources/nature/wedecliningbirdreport99reid.pdf Threatened and declining birds in the New South Wales Sheep-Wheat Belt: I. Diagnosis, characteristics and management]. Consultancy report to the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service. \u2013 CSIRO Wildlife and Ecology.</ref>\n\nAll subspecies of the jacky winter in [[Australia]] are declining. ''M. f. fascinans'' is declining throughout [[eastern Australia]], including [[New South Wales]], [[Queensland]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]];<ref name=\"wood\" /><ref name=\"rei\" /><ref name=\"fo\" /> ''M. f. assimilis'' is declining throughout [[Western Australia]] and parts of [[South Australia]];<ref name=\"reid\" /><ref name=\"re\" /> ''M. f. pallida'' is declining throughout parts of [[Queensland]], the [[Northern Territory]], as well as the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley]] in Western Australia.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Threats ==\n\nA number of species of woodland birds, such as the jacky winter, are declining and going locally [[extinct]], due to the [[habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and [[habitat degradation|degradation]] of their habitats. These deleterious changes are not only happening in [[Australia]], but around the world.<ref name=\"fo\">Ford, H. A. 2011. [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?paper=MU09115 The causes of decline of birds of eucalypt woodlands: advances in our knowledge over the last 10 years]. \u2013 Emu 111: 1-9. {{DOI|10.1071/MU09115}}</ref><ref>Ford, H. A., Barrett, G. W., Saunders, D. A. and Recher, H. F. 2001. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320700001014 Why have birds in the woodlands of Southern Australia declined?] - Biol. Cons. 97: 71-88.</ref><ref>Watson, J., Watson, A., Paull, D. and Freudenberger, D. 2003. [http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=876432789629323;res=IELNZC Woodland fragmentation is causing the decline of species and functional groups of birds in southeastern Australia]. \u2013 Pac. Cons. Bio 8: 261-270. {{ISSN|1038-2097}}</ref> Since [[Europe]]an settlement in [[Australia]], much of the woodlands have been converted to [[arable land]] and [[pasture]], for crops to grow and for livestock to graze.<ref name=\"fo\" /> Grazing livestock has impacted the jacky winter by decreasing the amount of small, ground and shrub vegetation, creating a lot of bare ground. This bare ground disadvantages the ground-pouncing jacky winter because a decrease in the larger terrestrial arthropods that they feed upon occurs.<ref name=\"rec\">Recher, H. F., Davis, W. E. and Calver, M. C. 2002. [http://researchrepository.murdoch.edu.au/1009/1/Comparative_foraging_ecology_2002.pdf Comparative foraging ecology of five species of ground-pouncing birds in western Australian woodlands with comments on species decline.] \u2013 Ornithol. Sci. 1: 29-40.</ref>\n\nThe increase of bare ground created by woodland fragmentation and degradation can also cause nesting resources of the jacky winter to become scarce due to the increase of weeds in the area. This results in the jacky winter having to try to find another suitable habitat.<ref name=\"keas\">Keast, A. 1995. [http://rzsnsw.metapress.com/content/pv8350n413016014/ Habitat loss and species loss: the birds of Sydney 50 years ago and now.] \u2013 Aust. Zool. 30: 3-25. {{DOI|10.7882/AZ.1995.002}}</ref><ref>Keast, A. 1996. [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4088938?sid=21106224360653&uid=3737536&uid=2&uid=4 Wing shape in insectivorous passerines inhabiting New Guinea and Australian rain-forests and eucalypt forest/eucalypt woodlands.] \u2013 Auk 113: 94-104. {{ISSN|0004-8038}}</ref><ref name=\"fo\" /> Finding suitable habitats though has become quite difficult for the jacky winter as other birds thrive in these landscapes. The [[noisy miner]] (''Manorina melancephala'') is a winner of these human altered landscapes and is quite aggressive towards other small [[insectivores]] such as the jacky winter. The jacky winter suffers quite negatively due to the noisy miner as it cannot outcompete it for food resources. The noisy miner has quite a negative impact on tree health, also limiting nesting material of the jacky winter.<ref>Debus, S. J. S. 2008. [http://www.une.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/30143/debus-n-miner.pdf The effect of Noisy Miners in small bush birds]: an unofficial cull and its outcome. - Pac. Cons. Bio. 14: 185-190. {{ISSN|1038-2097}}</ref>\n\n[[Climate change]] also threatens to cause the jacky winter to decline even further. A changing climate caused by [[Climate change|anthropogenic]] sources has already been determined to affect the breeding activity, the timing of [[Bird migration|migration]] and also the [[geographical]] and elevation range of birds quite significantly. These are seen all over the world on a number of different species.<ref>Neuh\u04d3user, M. 2007. [http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_54_2_79.pdf Climate change and the arrival of self-introduced bird species in New Zealand]. \u2013 Notornis. 54: 11-14.</ref><ref>Meijer, T., Nienaber, U., Langer, U. and Trillmich, F. 1999. [https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v101n01/p0124-p0132.pdf Temperature and timing of egg laying of European Starlings]. \u2013 Condor. 101: 124-132 {{DOI|10.2307/1370453}}\n</ref><ref name=\"mac\">Mac Nally, R., Bennett, A. F., Thomson, J. R., Radford, J. Q., Unmack, G., Horrocks, G. and Vesk, P. A. 2009. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00578.x/full Collapse of an avifauna: climate change appears to exacerbate habitat loss and degradation]. \u2013 Diversity Distrib. 15: 720-730. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00578}}.</ref><ref>Peh, K. S. H. 2007. [http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109%5B437:PEOCCO%5D2.0.CO%3B2 Potential effects of climate change on elevational distributions of tropical birds in Southeast Asia]. \u2013 Condor. 109: 437-441. {{DOI|10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109}}</ref> What threatens the jacky winter in Australia is increasing temperature and evapotranspiration, causing more droughts and increasing fire severity and frequency.<ref name=\"mac\" /><ref>Lindenmayer, D. B., Wood, J. T., Cunningham, R. B., MacGregor, C., Crane, M., Michael, M., Montague-Drake, R., Brown, B., Muntz, R. and Gill, A. M. 2008. [http://www.esajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1890/07-1943.1 Testing hypotheses associated with bird responses to wildfire]. \u2013 Ecological Application. 18: 1967-1983. {{DOI|10.1890/07-1943.1}}</ref> It is expected that these will impact availability of food, as well as safe nesting sites and refuges from predators.<ref>Ford, H. A., Walters, J. R., Cooper, C. B., Debus, S. J. S. and Doerr, V. A. J. 2009. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320709003991 Extinction debt or habitat change? \u2013 Ongoing losses of woodland birds in north-eastern New South Wales, Australia]. \u2013 Biol. Cons. 142: 3182-3190.</ref> The increasing temperature has already caused birds around the world to decrease in body size. This has been interpreted as a micro evolutionary response to global climate warming and the changes in nutrition associated with food availability and habitat quality which the jacky winter is undergoing in southeastern Australia.<ref>Gardner, J. L., Heinsohn, R. and Joseph, L. 2009. [http://classic.rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/early/2009/08/12/rspb.2009.1011.full Shifting latitudinal clines in avian body size correlate with global warming in Australian passerines]. \u2013 Proc. R. Soc. B \u2013 1-8. {{ISSN|1471-2954}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|Microeca fascinans}}\n{{Wikispecies|Microeca fascinans}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1033170}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:winter, jacky}}\n[[Category:Microeca|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Latham (ornithologist)|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jacky winter \n| image = Jacky Winter - Glen Davis.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704769/0 |title=''Microeca fascinans'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Microeca\n| species = fascinans\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''jacky winter''' (''Microeca fascinans'') is a small grey-brown robin found commonly throughout [[Australia]] and also in [[Papua New Guinea]]. The jacky winter acquired its name due to rapid and strong vocalisations, which sound like ''jacky-jacky winter-winter''.<ref name=Simpson>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia ISBN 067087918-5.</ref> Their call is also often referred to as sounding like ''peter-peter-peter''.<ref name=Slater>Slater, Peter (1974) A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines. Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref> Its habitats include open woodlands and farmlands.\n\n== Taxonomy and distribution ==\n\nThe jacky winter belongs to the family of [[Australasia]]n robins and flycatchers ''[[Petroicidae]]''. This family includes around 49 species in around 19 genera that are all endemic to [[Australasia]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref><ref>Loynes, K., Joseph, L. and Keogh, J. S. 2009. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790309002000 Multi-locus phylogeny clarifies the systematics of the Australo-Papuan robins (Family Petroicidae, Passeriformes)]. \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 53: 212-219. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2009.05.012}}</ref> The family ''[[Petroicidae]]'' evolved in a similar way to the [[Australo-Papuan]] warblers (''[[Acanthizidae]]'')\u2014the latter evolved in isolation from similar families to them, namely ''[[Parulidae]]'' and ''[[Sylviidae]]'', which occupied comparable niches in other continental regions, such as [[Central America|Central]][[South America|/South America]] and [[Eurasia]], respectively.<ref>Ericson, p. G. P., Irestedt, M. and Johansson, U.S. 2003. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03121.x/abstract?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&userIsAuthenticated=false Evolution, biogeography, and patters of diversification in passerine birds]. \u2013 J. Avian. Biol. 34: 3-15. {{DOI|10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03121.x}}</ref> ''[[Petroicidae]]'' evolved in the [[Australo-Papuan]] area to fill an ecological niche, which was already being used by New World flycatchers (''[[Tyrannidae]]'') in [[North America]] and [[South America]], and by Old World flycatchers (''[[Muscicapidae]]'') in [[Europe]], [[Africa]], and [[Asia]]. This is an example of [[convergent evolution]].<ref name=\"Chris\">Christidis, L., Irestedt, M., Rowe, D., Boles, W. E. and Norman, J. A. 2011. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790311003587 Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA phylogenies reveal a complex evolutionary history in the Australasian robin (Passeriformes: Petroicidae).] \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 61: 726-738. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2011.08.014}}</ref><ref>Sangster, G., Alstrom, P., Forsmark, E. and Olsson, U. 2010. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790310003076 Multi-locus phylogenetic analysis of Old World chats and flycatchers reveals extensive paraphyly at family, subfamily and genus level (Aves Muscicapidae)] \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 57: 380-392. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2010.07.008}}</ref>\n\nThe generic name ''Microeca'' derives from the Greek ''micros'' meaning 'small' and ''oikos'' meaning 'house'. This refers to the fact that they build the smallest nest of any Australian bird.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref> The specific name ''fascinans'' is Latin for 'fascinating' and derives from ''fascinare'' meaning 'to bewitch'.<ref name=Helm></ref>\n\nOther vernacular names for the jacky winter are brown flycatcher, peter peter, postboy, spinks and stumpbird.<ref name=Slater></ref><ref>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref>\n\nThere are three races of jacky winter found in [[Australia]]. ''Microeca fascinans fascinans'' (''leucophaea'') is the most familiar race, and is found in central and eastern [[Queensland]], [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], and southeastern [[South Australia]]. There are also ''Microeca fascinans assimilis'', which is found in [[South Australia]] and south [[Western Australia]], and ''Microeca fascinans pallida'', which is found in northern and western [[Queensland]], [[Northern Territory]], and the [[Kimberley]] in Western Australia.<ref name=Simpson></ref><ref name=\"Chris\" /><ref>Morcombe, Michael (2012) Field guide to Australian birds. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref><ref name=\"reid\">Reid, J. R. W. and Gillen, J. S. 2013. [http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/files/d137ff65-3033-48e5-8200-a2de00e18b97/cooper-catchment-2013-birds-rep.pdf. Riparian bird assembladges of Cooper Creek, South Australia]. \u2013 South Australian Arid Lands Natural Resources Management Board.</ref> ''Microeca fascinans zimmeri'' is a subspecies of jacky winter found in Papua New Guinea <ref>Bell, H. L. 2008. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1474-919X.1982.tb03772.x/abstract Abundance and seasonality of the savannah avifauna at Port Moresby, Papua New Guinea]. \u2013 Ibis 124: 252-274. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1474-919X.1982.tb03772.x}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nThe jacky winter is around 12 \u2013 14&nbsp;cm in length (including the tail) and its weight varies from 14 \u2013 18 g.<ref name=\"wood\">Wood, K. A, Thompson, N. and Ley, A. J. 2008. [http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=407981259692578;res=IELHSS Breeding Territories and Breeding Success of the Jacky Winter Microeca fasinans in South-eastern Queensland]. \u2013 Australian Field Ornithology 25: 121-131. {{ISSN|1448-0107}}</ref> The plumage of ''M. f. fascinans'' includes a greyish breast with white on the bottom half, its head and back is greyish-brown, while its wings are a darker brown with white edges. The bill is black, it has a narrow eye-line and a buff [[alula]] stripe. The tail of ''M. f. fascinans'' is blackish brown with white outer feathers. Its legs are black. Subspecies ''M. f. assimilis'' is very similar to ''M. f. fascinans''; however, it is darker, with more grey over the breast and flanks, covering up the white which is seen on ''M. f. fascinans''.<ref name=\"wood\" /> ''M. f. pallida'' is smaller than the other two subspecies, being only around 13&nbsp;cm. ''M. f. pallida'' is much more pallid than the other subspecies, and is usually a sandy brown colour.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Behaviour ==\n[[File:Jacky-winter96.ogg|thumb|300px|Rush Creek, south-east Queensland]]\n\nThe jacky winter can be heard vocalising before sunrise and usually stops towards the middle of the day. Occasionally closer to sunset, it can be heard again.<ref name=\"Kea\">Keast, A. 1994. [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?paper=MU9940230 The Annual Cycle in a Vocalisation Context: a Comparison of the Eastern Yellow Robin Eopsaltria australis and the Jacky Winter Microeca leucophaea.] \u2013 Emu 94: 230-238. {{doi|10.1071/MU9940230}}</ref> During the day they can be seen perched atop trees and posts, [[preening]] their [[feathers]] or even sunning to kill the [[parasites]], which may be present in amongst the feathers.<ref>Moyer, B. R. and Wagenbach, G. E. 1995. [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4089047?sid=21106224627453&uid=3737536&uid=4&uid=2 Sunning by Black Noddies (''Anous minutus'') may kill chewing lice (''Quadraceps hopkinsi'')]. \u2013 Auk. 112: 1073-1077. {{ISSN|0004-8038}}</ref>\n\n=== Diet ===\n\nThe jacky winter is an [[insectivore]] and a sit-and-search [[predator]], which moves amongst perches to locate food. This is a continuous activity that can cover long distances in order to find prey items.<ref name=\"rec\" /> The jacky winter has two methods of hunting, which include hawking and ground-pouncing. Hawking is when a bird flies and drops to the ground, grabbing their prey during flight, while ground-pouncing is when they fly from a perch, grabbing prey as they land.<ref name=\"mill\">Miller, J. R. and Cale, P. 2000. [http://www.esajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1890/1051-0761(2000)010%5B1732:BMAHUB%5D2.0.CO%3B2 Behavioural mechanisms and habitat use by birds in a fragmented agricultural landscape]. \u2013 Ecological Application. 10: 1732-1748. {{DOI|10.1890/1051-0761(2000)010}}</ref> Both of these hunting styles are used quite commonly by the jacky winter.<ref name=\"rec\" /><ref name=\"mill\" /><ref name=\"re\">Recher, H. F. and Davis Jr, W. E. 2002. [http://www.rswa.org.au/publications/Journal/85%282%29/recher85%282%29.pdf Foraging profile of a Salmon Gum woodland avifauna in Western Australia.] - Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia. 85: 103-111.</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Jacky winter nesting.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Female nesting]]\nIn many species of birds, the male plumage is quite bright and flamboyant to attract the opposite sex in hope of finding a partner to mate with. The jacky winter is instead a [[sexually monomorphic]] bird, which means that both the male and female are almost identical in appearance.<ref name=\"wood\" /> Rather than plumage playing a significant role in attracting the opposite sex, the jacky winter male uses song to attract a female during courtship.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> In the eastern states of Australia, the jacky winter breeds mostly to the west of the Great Dividing Range, where a suitable habitat of eucalyptus woodland is present. They build a small, open cup-shaped [[nest]], which is often made from grass and bark strips held together by spider webs. The nest is built in an exposed position, usually on a fork of a branch.<ref name=\"wood\" />\n\nThe breeding season of jacky winters occurs from September to November. Leading up to September, singing from the males is at its highest peak, then as the [[nestlings]] are born around late September, the singing becomes quite minimal.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> In late October, the singing increases again, lasting until early November, when the females lay a second [[brooding|brood]] of the season. By late November with the hatching of the young, the males stop singing, making vocalisations almost non-existent from then on. It stays like this until the birds have left the area.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> The nesting period lasts for 15 to 20 days, while the [[Egg incubation|incubation]] is between 16 and 18 days. Only the female will [[Egg incubation|incubate]] the eggs, while the male will help feed the young once they have hatched. 92 per cent of the time, the female will lay only two eggs per clutch.<ref name=\"wood\" />  It is uncommon for this number to vary, since many different [[environment (biophysical)|environmental]] factors determine the number of eggs per clutch in order to maximize the survival rate of fledglings from the nest.<ref>Winkler, D. W. and Walter, J. R. 1983. [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-4615-6781-3_2 The determination of clutch size in precocial birds]. \u2013 Current Ornithology. 1: 33-68. {{DOI|10.1007/978-1-4615-6781-3_2}}</ref>\n\nTerritory size of the jacky winter has been recorded at 1.7 ha, which is similar to other species of ''[[Petroicidae]]'', such as the [[flame robin]] and [[scarlet robin]]. The jacky winter seems to favour habitats for breeding that contain a [[eucalyptus]] box woodland or open box woodland, which have patches of box trees and isolated live trees. Fallen logs and stumps are also favoured in habitat selection.<ref name=\"wood\" /> The jacky winter holds these territories by perching on top of these eucalyptus trees and keeping a regular sustained call. The breeding density of jacky winters is about 17.2&nbsp;ha for one pair.<ref name=\"wood\" /> The jacky winter is known to defend their territory all year around.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Status ==\n\nThe jacky winter is a common species of bird found throughout [[Australia]], and is described as a bird of [[least concern]] by the [[IUCN]] (International Union for Conservation of Nature). Like many other small woodland birds in [[Australia]], the jacky winter populations are declining and are considered to be a common species but decreasing.<ref name=\"rei\">Reid, J. R. W. 1999. [http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/resources/nature/wedecliningbirdreport99reid.pdf Threatened and declining birds in the New South Wales Sheep-Wheat Belt: I. Diagnosis, characteristics and management]. Consultancy report to the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service. \u2013 CSIRO Wildlife and Ecology.</ref>\n\nAll subspecies of the jacky winter in [[Australia]] are declining. ''M. f. fascinans'' is declining throughout [[eastern Australia]], including [[New South Wales]], [[Queensland]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]];<ref name=\"wood\" /><ref name=\"rei\" /><ref name=\"fo\" /> ''M. f. assimilis'' is declining throughout [[Western Australia]] and parts of [[South Australia]];<ref name=\"reid\" /><ref name=\"re\" /> ''M. f. pallida'' is declining throughout parts of [[Queensland]], the [[Northern Territory]], as well as the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley]] in Western Australia.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Threats ==\n\nA number of species of woodland birds, such as the jacky winter, are declining and going locally [[extinct]], due to the [[habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and [[habitat degradation|degradation]] of their habitats. These deleterious changes are not only happening in [[Australia]], but around the world.<ref name=\"fo\">Ford, H. A. 2011. [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?paper=MU09115 The causes of decline of birds of eucalypt woodlands: advances in our knowledge over the last 10 years]. \u2013 Emu 111: 1-9. {{DOI|10.1071/MU09115}}</ref><ref>Ford, H. A., Barrett, G. W., Saunders, D. A. and Recher, H. F. 2001. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320700001014 Why have birds in the woodlands of Southern Australia declined?] - Biol. Cons. 97: 71-88.</ref><ref>Watson, J., Watson, A., Paull, D. and Freudenberger, D. 2003. [http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=876432789629323;res=IELNZC Woodland fragmentation is causing the decline of species and functional groups of birds in southeastern Australia]. \u2013 Pac. Cons. Bio 8: 261-270. {{ISSN|1038-2097}}</ref> Since [[Europe]]an settlement in [[Australia]], much of the woodlands have been converted to [[arable land]] and [[pasture]], for crops to grow and for livestock to graze.<ref name=\"fo\" /> Grazing livestock has impacted the jacky winter by decreasing the amount of small ground and shrub vegetation, creating a lot of bare ground. This bare ground disadvantages the ground-pouncing jacky winter, because of a decrease in the larger terrestrial arthropods that they feed upon occurs.<ref name=\"rec\">Recher, H. F., Davis, W. E. and Calver, M. C. 2002. [http://researchrepository.murdoch.edu.au/1009/1/Comparative_foraging_ecology_2002.pdf Comparative foraging ecology of five species of ground-pouncing birds in western Australian woodlands with comments on species decline.] \u2013 Ornithol. Sci. 1: 29-40.</ref>\n\nThe increase of bare ground created by woodland fragmentation and degradation can also cause nesting resources of the jacky winter to become scarce due to the increase of weeds in the area. This results in the jacky winter having to try to find another suitable habitat.<ref name=\"keas\">Keast, A. 1995. [http://rzsnsw.metapress.com/content/pv8350n413016014/ Habitat loss and species loss: the birds of Sydney 50 years ago and now.] \u2013 Aust. Zool. 30: 3-25. {{DOI|10.7882/AZ.1995.002}}</ref><ref>Keast, A. 1996. [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4088938?sid=21106224360653&uid=3737536&uid=2&uid=4 Wing shape in insectivorous passerines inhabiting New Guinea and Australian rain-forests and eucalypt forest/eucalypt woodlands.] \u2013 Auk 113: 94-104. {{ISSN|0004-8038}}</ref><ref name=\"fo\" /> Finding suitable habitats though has become quite difficult for the jacky winter as other birds thrive in these landscapes. The [[noisy miner]] (''Manorina melancephala'') is a winner of these human altered landscapes and is quite aggressive towards other small [[insectivores]] such as the jacky winter. The jacky winter suffers quite negatively due to the noisy miner as it cannot outcompete it for food resources. The noisy miner has quite a negative impact on tree health, also limiting nesting material of the jacky winter.<ref>Debus, S. J. S. 2008. [http://www.une.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/30143/debus-n-miner.pdf The effect of Noisy Miners in small bush birds]: an unofficial cull and its outcome. - Pac. Cons. Bio. 14: 185-190. {{ISSN|1038-2097}}</ref>\n\n[[Climate change]] also threatens to cause the jacky winter to decline even further. A changing climate caused by [[Climate change|anthropogenic]] sources has already been determined to affect the breeding activity, the timing of [[Bird migration|migration]] and also the [[geographical]] and elevation range of birds quite significantly. These are seen all over the world on a number of different species.<ref>Neuh\u04d3user, M. 2007. [http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_54_2_79.pdf Climate change and the arrival of self-introduced bird species in New Zealand]. \u2013 Notornis. 54: 11-14.</ref><ref>Meijer, T., Nienaber, U., Langer, U. and Trillmich, F. 1999. [https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v101n01/p0124-p0132.pdf Temperature and timing of egg laying of European Starlings]. \u2013 Condor. 101: 124-132 {{DOI|10.2307/1370453}}\n</ref><ref name=\"mac\">Mac Nally, R., Bennett, A. F., Thomson, J. R., Radford, J. Q., Unmack, G., Horrocks, G. and Vesk, P. A. 2009. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00578.x/full Collapse of an avifauna: climate change appears to exacerbate habitat loss and degradation]. \u2013 Diversity Distrib. 15: 720-730. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00578}}.</ref><ref>Peh, K. S. H. 2007. [http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109%5B437:PEOCCO%5D2.0.CO%3B2 Potential effects of climate change on elevational distributions of tropical birds in Southeast Asia]. \u2013 Condor. 109: 437-441. {{DOI|10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109}}</ref> What threatens the jacky winter in Australia is increasing temperature and evapotranspiration, causing more droughts and increasing fire severity and frequency.<ref name=\"mac\" /><ref>Lindenmayer, D. B., Wood, J. T., Cunningham, R. B., MacGregor, C., Crane, M., Michael, M., Montague-Drake, R., Brown, B., Muntz, R. and Gill, A. M. 2008. [http://www.esajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1890/07-1943.1 Testing hypotheses associated with bird responses to wildfire]. \u2013 Ecological Application. 18: 1967-1983. {{DOI|10.1890/07-1943.1}}</ref> It is expected that these will impact availability of food, as well as safe nesting sites and refuges from predators.<ref>Ford, H. A., Walters, J. R., Cooper, C. B., Debus, S. J. S. and Doerr, V. A. J. 2009. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320709003991 Extinction debt or habitat change? \u2013 Ongoing losses of woodland birds in north-eastern New South Wales, Australia]. \u2013 Biol. Cons. 142: 3182-3190.</ref> The increasing temperature has already caused birds around the world to decrease in body size. This has been interpreted as a micro evolutionary response to global climate warming and the changes in nutrition associated with food availability and habitat quality which the jacky winter is undergoing in southeastern Australia.<ref>Gardner, J. L., Heinsohn, R. and Joseph, L. 2009. [http://classic.rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/early/2009/08/12/rspb.2009.1011.full Shifting latitudinal clines in avian body size correlate with global warming in Australian passerines]. \u2013 Proc. R. Soc. B \u2013 1-8. {{ISSN|1471-2954}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|Microeca fascinans}}\n{{Wikispecies|Microeca fascinans}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1033170}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:winter, jacky}}\n[[Category:Microeca|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Latham (ornithologist)|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThreats:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacky_winter"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n| image           = Corona Lockdown Tirupur, Tamil Nadu (2).jpg\n| width           = \n| caption         = Empty store shelves in [[Tiruppur]] due to panic buying prior to lockdown\n| map1            = TN COVID-19 cases in districts.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 5 April)\n{{legend|#542200ff|50+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#d45500ff|30-49 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ff9955ff|10\u201329 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffe6d5ff|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 834<ref name=\"TNHFW\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Home|access-date=2020-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331222637/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MB-9Apr\"/>\n| active_cases    = 799<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/><ref name=\"MB-9Apr\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 27<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/><ref name=\"MB-9Apr\"/>\n| deaths          = 8<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/><ref name=\"MB-9Apr\"/>\n| territories     = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#COVID-19 cases by districts|33 districts]]\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was reported on 7 March 2020. The [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Health and Family Welfare]] has confirmed a total of 834 cases, including 8 deaths and 27 recoveries, as of 9 April 2020.<ref name=\"MB-9Apr\"/><ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n\n763 ({{Percentage|763|834}}) of all reported cases were from one cluster linked to an Islamic religious congregation event [[Tablighi Jamaat]] that took place in [[Delhi]].<ref name=\"MB-9Apr\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulte.com/news/83733/More-Than-330-Cases-Linked-to-Delhi-Mosque|title=More Than 330 Cases Linked to Delhi Mosque|last=13|date=2020-04-02|website=Gulte|language=english|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The state government has created containment zones in 16 affected districts to screen residents for checking community spread and to prevent more infections.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329134259/https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"containmentDH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-74-nizamuddin-link-to-a-chunk-of-it-surfaces-819633.html|title=Tamil Nadu coronavirus cases rises to 74, Nizamuddin link to a chunk of it surfaces|date=2020-03-31|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== March ===\nThe first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from Delhi to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319193205/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319161417/https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324184127/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328044912/https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"28Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328125841/https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329142751/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|archive-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"29Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070556/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"30MarchBulletinOld\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), [[Kanyakumari district|Kanyakumari]] (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), [[Madurai district|Madurai]] (2) and [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]] (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070737/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" /> The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331163219/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day ''[[Tablighi Jamaat]]'' congregation in [[Nizamuddin Markaz Mosque|Nizamuddin Markaz mosque]], [[New Delhi]] in early March.<ref name=\"March31-DH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401020556/https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It faced difficulty while trying to map the rest. It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331211819/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this, the Nizamuddin Markaz emerged as a new virus hotspot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html|title=How Nizamuddin markaz became Covid-19 hotspot; more than 8,000 attendees identified|date=2020-04-02|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162727/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html|archive-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nOn 1 April, the state reported 110 new cases, all attended the Delhi Nizamuddin event. The total became 234.<ref name=\"April1-IT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-new-coronavirus-cases-linked-nizamuddin-event-tabligh-1662243-2020-04-01|title=Tamil Nadu reports 110 new coronavirus cases, all linked to Nizamuddin event|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|title=110 more cases in Tamil Nadu on Wednesday, all attended Delhi Jamaat conference|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402005422/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|archive-date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary Beela Rajesh said that 1103  out of 1500 attendees of the event had been traced and isolated. 658 of their samples had been tested of which,190 tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu witnesses steep rise in cases|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401210601/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the participants approached officials themselves after government's request.<ref name=\":2\" /> Family members and close contacts were either taken to quarantine facilities or home quarantined.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/special-containment-plan-for-tj-group/articleshow/74939483.cms|title=Tamil Nadu: Special containment plan for Tablighi Jamaat group {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=08:57}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, 75 new cases were reported, of which 74 of them attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB_april02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_02_04_20_COVID_19_6_PM.pdf|title=Media Bulletin April 02|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, 102 new cases were reported, of which 100 were Delhi event participants. Two others were from Chennai, one with [[Comorbidity|co-morbid]] condition and one US-returnee.<ref name=\"MB-Apr3\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404185030/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=4 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, 74 new cases were reported, of which 69 were Delhi event participants, 4 were contacts of the event participants. One was from Chennai.<ref name=\"TheHinduApr04\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/74-new-cases-take-tamil-nadus-total-to-485/article31259992.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} 74 new cases take Tamil Nadu's total to 485|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405032029/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/74-new-cases-take-tamil-nadus-total-to-485/article31259992.ece|archive-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> Two more deaths were reported, a 51 years old male who attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' at Villupuram and a female at Theni Government hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/two-dead-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu/article31258200.ece#|title=Two dead of Covid-19 in Tamil Nadu|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055948/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/two-dead-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu/article31258200.ece|archive-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, 86 new cases were reported of which 85 are related to Delhi event directly or indirectly. A 71 year old from Ramanathapuram who died on Thursday was tested positive. A 60 year old also died in the same hospital as previous patient.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sujatha|first=R.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tn-reports-86-more-covid-19-cases-total-spikes-to-571/article31263138.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Tamil Nadu reports 86 new cases, two more patients die|date=2020-04-05|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406035038/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tn-reports-86-more-covid-19-cases-total-spikes-to-571/article31263138.ece|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health department revealed that 1246 contacts of Tablighi Jamaat participants have been traced and isolated so far.<ref name=\"MB-Apr5\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405215542/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=5 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, 50 new cases were reported bringing the total cases to 621. 48 of them were returnees of Delhi event.<ref name=\"MB-Apr6\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406132432/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|archive-date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> 101 people who attended a COVID-19 victim's burial were home-quarantined in [[Ramanathapuram district|Ramanathapuram]]. They were not aware of his condition as the test result returned positive after only two days his burial.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/06/over-100-quarantined-after-covid-19-victim-buried-without-precautions-in-tamil-nadu-2126260.html|title=Over 100 quarantined after COVID-19 victim buried without precautions in Tamil Nadu|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123052/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/06/over-100-quarantined-after-covid-19-victim-buried-without-precautions-in-tamil-nadu-2126260.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, 69 new cases were reported, of which 63 were related to Delhi event.<ref name=\"MB-7Apr2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407141921/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 48 new cases were reported bringing total to 738. 42 of those are connected to ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB-8Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408133536/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=8 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> One among the 42 is a Malaysian national. Government had revealed that 1480 attendees of the Delhi event were traced and isolated. 1716 samples from them and their contacts were tested, of which 679 had returned positive.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/09/tamil-nadu-reports-48-new-covid19-cases-tally-climbs-to-738-2127606.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 48 new COVID19 cases, tally climbs to 738|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the state reported 96 new cases which brought the total cases to 834.<ref name=\"MB-9Apr\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409140149/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|archive-date=9 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases}}\n=== COVID-19 cases by districts ===\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\">{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases by district}}</div>\n\n=== Number of samples analysed per week ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width: 40%;\"\"\n!style=\"width: 5%;\"|Week\n!style=\"width: 10%;\"|New\n!style=\"width: 10%;\"|Total\n!style=\"width: 5%;\"|Sources(s)\n|-\n!Till 9 March\n|59\n|59\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin090320COVID19.pdf|title=MediaBulletin090320COVID19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070803/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin090320COVID19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!9\u201316 March\n|37\n|96\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin160320COVID19.pdf|title=MediaBulletin160320COVID19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070825/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin160320COVID19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!16\u201323 March\n|416\n|512\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_23_03_20_%20COVID_19.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_23_03_20_%20COVID_19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070850/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_23_03_20_%20COVID_19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 202